"text-align:left;">The Blacksheep Story Part III</p>
<div style="margin:0px;padding:0px;text-align:left;">
You finally managed to find the best possible scores for Blacksheeps virtual reality game. Strangely enough Blacksheep himself has already made a better score than the best you calculated. You suspected skullduggery and in fact it has been mentioned that Blacksheep might not be human. You decide to test this hypothesis and have managed to obtain a sample of Blacksheeps DNA.<br />
<table cellspacing="0" style="margin:1mm;border-width:0px;"><tr><td style="padding:0px;background-color:#000000;vertical-align:middle;border:1px solid #FFFFFF;" rowspan="2">
<img src="dna2.jpg" style="margin:0px;border-width:0px;" /></td><td style="padding:0mm 0mm 0mm 2mm;color:#FFFFFF;font-size:12pt;vertical-align:top;">In order to test the DNA we you must try to match it against a human DNA strand. It is necessary to find the longest subsequence of DNA pairs present in both DNA strands, this will enable you to determine how similar the strands are.<br /> Lets take an example, if the DNA pairs were:<p style="text-align:left;" class="challenge_1">1. CATGGCATG<br />
2. ATCATTCAT</p> 
Then the longest subsequence is CATCAT, because it occurs in both DNA strands in the order C, A, T, C, A, T.<br /><br />Now <a href="s1.txt" class="challenge_1">here are the DNA strands</a> for you. Note that, in general, the longest subsequence is not unique. Therefore we want the particular sequence that can be described as follows: let <span class="mono">s1</span> and <span class="mono">s2</span> be the two DNA pairs, let <span class="mono">s1</span> have length <span class="mono">n</span> and <span class="mono">s2</span> have length <span class="mono">m</span>, and let <span class="mono">s1_1</span> up to <span class="mono">s1_n</span> be the <span class="mono">n</span> characters of <span class="mono">s1</span> and <span class="mono">s2_1</span> to <span class="mono">s2_m</span> be the <span class="mono">m</span> characters of <span class="mono">s2</span>. Finally let <span class="mono">L(x,y)</span> be the length of the longest sequence for <span class="mono">s1_1</span> to <span class="mono">s1_x</span> and <span class="mono">s2_1</span> to <span class="mono">s2_y</span>. If <span class="mono">L(x,y)==L(x-1,y)==L(x,y-1)</span> then your answer should be the string that was generated by <span class="mono">L(x-1,y)</span>.</td></tr><tr><td style="padding:0mm 0mm 0mm 2mm;vertical-align:bottom;text-align:center;">
<div class="challenge_1" style="text-align:center;font-weight:bold;font-size:14pt;">Good luck!</div>
